        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "refactor: remove sender owner tool gating",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Remove the old sender-owner tool visibility gate, owner-only tool descriptors, and system-event owner-downgrade plumbing.\n- Keep `senderIsOwner` only where it is real identity metadata for command/channel-action auth, including Matrix actions and gateway/MCP loopback identity derivation.\n- Update tests, config schema/help, plugin descriptors, security scan rules, and changelog for the simplified trust model.\n\n## Verification\nBehavior addressed: configured agent tools stay visible in trusted sessions; external/system events no longer mutate sender owner state; command and channel-action auth still carry real sender identity where needed.\nReal environment tested: local macOS focused tests/typecheck; earlier AWS Crabbox Linux changed gate before the final narrow loopback identity cleanup.\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n- OPENCLAW_LOCAL_CHECK_MODE=throttled node scripts/run-tsgo.mjs -b tsconfig.projects.json\n- OPENCLAW_VITEST_MAX_WORKERS=1 node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/gateway/mcp-http.test.ts src/gateway/tools-invoke-http.test.ts src/agents/cli-runner/prepare.test.ts src/infra/outbound/message-action-params.test.ts src/agents/tools/message-tool.test.ts extensions/matrix/src/actions.test.ts extensions/matrix/src/actions.account-propagation.test.ts\n- OPENCLAW_VITEST_MAX_WORKERS=1 node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/agents/pi-tools.availability.test.ts\n- git diff --check\n- node scripts/crabbox-wrapper.mjs run --provider aws --shell -- \"env -u OPENCLAW_TESTBOX -u OPENCLAW_TESTBOX_REMOTE_RUN pnpm check:changed\"\nEvidence after fix: local typecheck passed; focused test shards passed 356 and 6 tests; git diff check passed; AWS Crabbox provider=aws lease=cbx_b5d68b633b9f run=run_8e419c2e0d4a passed with exit=0 before the final narrow loopback identity cleanup.\nObserved result after fix: configured tools stay visible while Matrix/channel-action owner auth still receives server-derived sender identity.\nWhat was not tested: live channel E2E after the final narrow loopback identity cleanup.\n\n## Review\nCodex autoreview accepted and fixed two real identity-source findings: `/tools/invoke` now derives sender owner identity from auth, and MCP loopback owner identity is token-derived server-side. The remaining repeated findings asking to restore owner-only tool filtering and system-event owner downgrades were rejected as the intentional trust-model change for this PR.\n",
